A permutation test showing what the F-test means:

n <- 1000
f.stats <- numeric(n)
my.fun <- function(x) { sum((x - mean(x))^2) }
sst <- my.fun(c0502$percent)           # total sum of squared resids
dft <- nrow(c0502) - 1                 # total degrees of freedom
dfb <- length(levels(c0502$judge)) - 1 # df between groups
dfw <- dft - dfb                       # df within groups
for (i in 1:n) {
   ssw <- sum(with(c0502, tapply(sample(percent), judge, my.fun)))
   msw <- ssw / dfw # mean squared resid, within groups
   msb <- (sst - ssw) / dfb
   f.stats[i] <- msb / msw
}
hist(f.stats, freq=F)
x <- seq(from=0,to=6,by=0.01)
y <- df(x,6,39)
lines(x,y)

Let me look more closely at the between/within sum of squares

my.fun <- function(x) { sum((x - mean(x))^2) }
sst <- my.fun(c0502$percent)
df.total <- nrow(c0502) - 1
df.between <- length(levels(c0502$judge)) - 1
df.within <- df.total - df.between
ssw <- sum(with(c0502, tapply(percent, judge, my.fun))) # SS within groups

grand.mean <- mean(c0502$percent)
group.means <- with(c0502, tapply(percent, judge, mean))
group.sizes <- with(c0502, tapply(percent, judge, length))
group.resids <- group.means - grand.mean

# the same:
sst - ssw
## [1] 1927
weighted.mean((group.means - grand.mean)^2, group.sizes) * nrow(c0502)
## [1] 1927

14. Spock - by hand t-test of Spocks judge vs judge A

  1. What is the pooled standard deviation?
spocks.percent <- 14.62
spocks.sd <- 5.039
spocks.n <- 9
a.n <- 5
a.percent <- 34.12
a.sd <- 11.942
(sd.pooled <- sqrt(((spocks.n-1)*spocks.sd^2 + (a.n-1)*a.sd^2)/
                      (spocks.n + a.n - 2)))
## [1] 8.029
  1. t-test
df.test <- spocks.n + a.n - 2
(se <- sd.pooled * sqrt(1/spocks.n + 1/a.n)) # standard error of (a - spock)
## [1] 4.478
(t <- (0 - (a.percent - spocks.percent)) / se)
## [1] -4.354
2 * pt(t, df=df.test)
## [1] 0.0009378
  1. Checking against a computer t-test:
ind <- with(ex0513, judge == "SPOCK'S" | judge == "A")
t.test(percent ~ judge, data=ex0513[ind,], var.equal=T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  percent by judge
## t = 4.354, df = 12, p-value = 0.0009384
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   9.74 29.26
## sample estimates:
##       mean in group A mean in group SPOCK'S 
##                 34.12                 14.62

18. Fatty Acid

ex0518 <- read.csv('ascii/ex0518.csv')
names(ex0518) <- tolower(names(ex0518))

A model assuming six independent groups, and plots of residual vs.day.

six <- aov(protein ~ treatmnt, ex0518)
plot(six$residuals ~ ex0518$day, main="All treatments", ylab="residuals", xlab="day")

with(ex0518, plot(six$residuals[ treatmnt != 'CONTROL'] ~ day[treatmnt != 'CONTROL'],
                  main="The non-control groups", ylab="residuals", xlab="day"))

with(ex0518, plot(six$residuals[ treatmnt == 'CONTROL'] ~ day[treatmnt == 'CONTROL'],
                  main="Just the control groups.", ylab="residuals", xlab="day"))

The residuals in the just control group are calculated in reference to the mean of the whole control group. So the plot shows that the observations jump around together from day to day. So the day seems to have an affect on the protein measurement.

The ten groups do not have equal means [shorthand for we reject the null hypothesis that the ten groups have equal means]:

ten <- aov(protein ~ trt.daygroup, ex0518)
anova(ten)
## Analysis of Variance Table

19. Cavity Size and Use - TODO - dont understand this one

species <- c('mouse', 'pinyon mouse', "Bewick's wren", 'mountain bluebird',
             'ash-throated flycatcher', 'plain titmouse', 'northern flicker',
             'western screech owl', 'american kestrel')
n <- c(127,44,24,41,18,16,11,7,6)
mn <- c(7.347,7.368,7.418,7.487,7.563,7.568,8.214,8.272,8.297)
sample.sd <- c(.4979,.4235,.3955,.3183,.3111,.4649,.2963,.3242,.5842)
ex0519 <- data.frame(species, n, mn, sample.sd)
  1. Compute the pooled estimate of variance.
(s2p <- with(ex0519, weighted.mean(sample.sd^2, n - 1))) # see pg. 120-121
## [1] 0.1919
  1. F-test
extra.df <- (9-1)
ssw <- with(ex0519, sample.sd^2 %*% (n-1))   # SS within groups
sst <- 0.4962^2 * (294-1)                # SS total (0.4962 is their given SD)
ssb <- sst - ssw                       # SS between groups
f <- (ssb / extra.df) / s2p
pf(f, df1 = extra.df, df2 = (294-1) - (9-1), lower.tail = F)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 5.668e-14

  1. Verify another way of calculating ssb.

  2. Sneaky way of checking whether my answers above were correct: making fake data and having R do the F-test.

sneaky.sample <- function(n, desired.sample.mean, desired.sample.sd) {
   x <- rnorm(n)
   x <- (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
   desired.sample.sd * x + desired.sample.mean
}
require(plyr)
## Loading required package: plyr
set.seed(5432)
fake.data <- ddply(ex0519, .(species), transform, sam = sneaky.sample(n, mn, sample.sd))
anova(aov(sam ~ species, data=fake.data))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: sam
##            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)    
## species     8   17.5   2.182    11.4 5.5e-14 ***
## Residuals 285   54.7   0.192                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
